Rating: 0
I followed the recipe almost to the letter - the changes I made were... No bacon, just because from reading the ingredients it sounded like it would be rich enough without it, and I was right. If the reviews that say this was too rich, greasy or salty put you off, just skip the bacon. I doubled the allspice, and also used about 1/8 tsp of grated nutmeg; it seemed like it would go with the hearty/savoury theme. This worked really well. If you want to try it with nutmeg but only have pre-ground, use about 1/4 tsp. And lastly I forgot to buy prunes, so I substituted 1/2 cup of sultanas, soaked in boiling water for 15 mins then drained and finely chopped. The onion and celery I chopped very finely, and I grated the carrot, because I was worried if there were big chunks of vegies it would make the loaf too crumbly and not hold together properly. As it turned out it was still too crumbly. A couple of commenters have said that using oatmeal instead of breadcrumbs keeps it more together, so I'll try that next time. Apart from the crumbliness this was an amazing meal. Tangy from the W sauce & vinegar, juicy from the pork & dried fruit, savoury from the beef & nutmeg. To all those commenters complaining about it being too fatty - did you even bother to TASTE the fat? I know it's hard in our Anglo-American food culture to view anything fatty as good, but the stuff that oozed out of this meatloaf was OUT OF THIS WORLD. We ate it as a condiment with the potatoes I roasted in the pan and some steamed broccoli, but you could turn it into a gravy with a splash of beef stock, some wine & flour, or save it to toss potatoes in before roasting them. Seriously, don't waste precious pork fat. Those of you who who threw the fat in the bin: there is a special hell for you.

