Rating: 0
The forum is perhaps a better place to discuss this, but I wanted to comment on the role of reviewers on Epicurious. I recently defended my dissertation on the rhetoric of cooking Web sites like Epicurious. The reviews were one of the features that made Epicurious strikingly different from other sites. I like recipes that anticipate the realities of modern suburban homes, but Epicurious recipes often do not. So I either muddle along on my own with occasional success or I hope other Epi members are in the same pot as I. Usually they are and they tell me about it in their recipe reviews. The reviews following each recipe co-opt the authoritarian voice of recipes and always describe reviewers' successes and failures with substitutions. They make the changes based on what was available in their kitchens or based on their families palates. They add ingredients. They leave out ingredients. Reviews admit mistakes the cooks make or critique the recipes. Others discuss changes they would make if they made the recipe again. Many reviews specifically reference other reviews so it is clear that users read and value the comments of others in the Epi community. Users are making knowledge collaboratively and valuing that collaborative, experiential knowledge. I'm going to make this meatloaf this week and I'll post again with my review (and likely my substitutions).

