This was, without a doubt, the best meatloaf I've had. My husband, something of a purist in this matter, concurred, even after he knew about the prunes. I essentially halved the recipe, since it's just the two of us, and used all beef since I didn't have any pork (I did, fortunately, have bacon). I did use 2 eggs, though, for extra binding. I upped the oven temp a bit to make sure it formed a nice crust before it cooked through, since the smaller loaf cooks faster (40 minutes or so to 155). I urge you to try this - it's nothing like the stuff with Lipton soup your mother/grandmother used to make.

Rating: 0
Significant variations, so I didn't rate it, but I really liked this recipe as a base. I used brioche instead of sandwich bread, 2% milk instead of whole, vegetarian Worcestershire sauce (it was all I had in the house), no bacon, about 1/4 cup apricot preserves instead of the prunes, no pork, a total of 2 lbs ground beef and 1/2 lb ground turkey breast, 3 eggs and no parsley. (Whew!). I really liked the flavors, but it was definitely different from a typical meatloaf. I like mine uniforn in appearance, so before mixing the meat with everything else, I blended the latter in a food processor. I also used the processor to chop all the veggies and mince the garlic. When I added those to the pan, I chopped the bread in it and then added the milk to the same container. It was a lot quicker that way and used very few dishes, which was an added bonus. I was also really tired when I was making it, so I misread the recipe and completely spread the mixture out in a 9x13 pan. So it wasn't exactly a loaf, but it did cook more quickly (~30 minutes) and there was a nice lot of crust. Next time I plan to up the preserves by an extra 2 tablespoons, add some tomato paste (what can I say--I guess I'm a traditionalist!), and use textured vegetable protein (TVP) instead of the turkey. I was too tired to make potatoes, but a simple salad of mixed baby greens with a raspberry vinaigrette went well.

Rating: 4
The 4th fork is for the pleasant surprise. I'm not used to this whole "liking meatloaf" thing. The prunes were a great addition. I forgot to get pork, and the bacon in my fridge had gone bad, so I used 2 lbs of organic ground beef with an 85/15 fat ratio, and will probably use a lower fat content next time, because it was swimming in fat after baking even without the bacon and pork. Because I don't have a meat thermometer, I baked this in a ring shape so it would cook more evenly and would be easier to check for doneness (nod to Betty Crocker for the help on that one). It also made more of the yummy crust. My British husband likes gravy with just about everything, so I used some of the more-than- ample drippings and a small box of beef broth with some s&p and it came out well. I served with garlic mashed potatoes and a tossed salad and it was just the happiest thing that could have happened to my mouth. I definitely recommend this, the little carrots bits were great, and although I couldn't taste the celery or parsley, I'm sure they added something.

